SIMPLE: flagitious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flagitious
<hw>Fla*gi"tious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>flagitiosus</ets>, fr. <ets>flagitium</ets> a shameful or
disgraceful act, orig., a burning desire, heat of passion, from
<ets>flagitare</ets> to demand hotly, fiercely; cf. <ets>flagrare</ets>
to burn, E. <ets>flagrant</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disgracefully
or shamefully criminal; grossly wicked; scandalous; shameful; -- said of
acts, crimes, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Debauched principles and <qex>flagitious</qex> practices.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Guilty of enormous crimes; corrupt; profligate; --
said of persons.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by scandalous crimes or vices; <as>as,
<ex>flagitious</ex> times</as>.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Atrocious; villainous; flagrant; heinous;
corrupt; profligate; abandoned. See <er>Atrocious</er>.</syn></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Fla*gi"tious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Fla*gi"tious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sentence so <qex>flagitiously</qex> unjust.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flagman</ent>⟦br⟧
